      {
        "heading": "From Technique to Hunt",
        "content": "Knowing that an attacker used T1059.001 is interesting; being able to turn that knowledge into a detection or a hunt query is what makes you valuable to a SOC. The bridge from technique to hunt is the ATT&CK Data Sources field — every technique page lists the telemetry that reveals it, and your job is to translate that telemetry into a concrete search in whatever SIEM or EDR platform you use. This section walks the translation for a handful of high-value techniques so the pattern becomes second nature.\n\n### Start from the data source, not the technique name\n\nWhen you open a technique page, resist the urge to search for the technique's name in your logs — the name is a human abstraction that does not appear in telemetry. Instead, read the Data Sources. For PowerShell (T1059.001) the primary data sources are Command: Command Execution, Process: Process Creation, and Module: Module Load. That tells you to look at process-creation events (Windows Event ID 4688 or Sysmon Event ID 1) where the image is powershell.exe or pwsh.exe, and at the command-line field. Now you have something concrete to query.\n\n### Turn the procedure into detection logic\n\nThe procedure examples on the technique page give you the specific behaviors to hunt. For malicious PowerShell, the tell-tale procedures include encoded commands (-EncodedCommand or -enc), hidden windows (-WindowStyle Hidden or -w hidden), execution-policy bypass (-ExecutionPolicy Bypass or -ep bypass), no-profile (-nop), and download cradles that call Net.WebClient or Invoke-WebRequest. Each of these is a string you can match on the command-line field. Layer them: a single flag might be a legitimate admin, but encoded plus hidden plus a Word parent process is almost never benign. **The most powerful hunts combine a technique with its likely context** — here, the parent-child relationship (Office app spawning PowerShell) turns a noisy signal into a high-fidelity one.\n\n### Widen from one host to the whole environment\n\nA good hunt does not just find the one host that alerted; it sweeps the environment for the same technique to find other compromised hosts you did not know about. Once you have detection logic for the procedure, run it across all endpoints for the last thirty days. If your incident host ran an encoded downloader, other hosts running the same pattern are candidates for the same campaign. This is how a single alert becomes the discovery of a broader intrusion.\n\n### Validate against benign activity\n\nEvery hunt must account for false positives, because the whole point of a technique is that adversaries abuse legitimate functionality. PowerShell is used constantly by administrators, software installers, and management tools like SCCM and Intune. Before you promote a hunt to an always-on detection, baseline it: run the query, look at what normally matches, and add exclusions for your known-good service accounts, deployment tools, and admin jump hosts. The questions to ask are: **Who legitimately does this in my environment? What does their version of the behavior look like? How is the malicious version different?** The difference — the encoding, the parent process, the destination — is your detection.",
        "codeExample": "// Technique -> Hunt: T1059.001 (PowerShell) into a SIEM query\n// Data Sources from the ATT&CK page: Process: Process Creation, Command: Command Execution\n//\n// Splunk SPL (Sysmon EID 1) -- hunt malicious PowerShell procedures + high-fidelity context\nindex=sysmon EventCode=1 (Image=\"*\\\\powershell.exe\" OR Image=\"*\\\\pwsh.exe\")\n| eval cmd=lower(CommandLine)\n| eval enc=if(match(cmd,\"-enc|-e\\s|-encodedcommand\"),1,0)\n| eval hidden=if(match(cmd,\"-w\\s+hidden|-windowstyle\\s+hidden\"),1,0)\n| eval bypass=if(match(cmd,\"-ep\\s+bypass|-executionpolicy\\s+bypass|-nop\"),1,0)\n| eval cradle=if(match(cmd,\"net.webclient|invoke-webrequest|iwr|downloadstring\"),1,0)\n| eval office_parent=if(match(lower(ParentImage),\"winword|excel|powerpnt|outlook\"),1,0)\n| eval score = enc + hidden + bypass + cradle + (office_parent*2)\n| where score >= 2\n| stats values(CommandLine) as commands, values(ParentImage) as parents,\n        max(score) as risk by Computer, User\n| sort - risk\n// Then: sweep all hosts for the same pattern; exclude known SCCM/Intune/admin accounts."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Why Mapping Matters for Reporting and Coverage",
        "content": "Mapping investigations to ATT&CK is not paperwork you do after the real work is done — it is what turns individual incidents into organizational learning, measurable defensive posture, and clear communication with the people who fund the SOC. An analyst who maps every case builds a personal and team-wide asset that pays off long after the incident is closed.\n\n### ATT&CK in the incident report\n\nA well-written incident report tells the story of the intrusion as a sequence of techniques. Instead of a prose blob, you present a clean chain: Initial Access via T1566.001 (spearphishing attachment), Execution via T1059.001 (PowerShell), Persistence via T1547.001 (registry Run key), Command and Control via T1071.001 (web protocols), and Impact via T1486 (data encrypted for impact). This does three things. It makes the report skimmable for a technical reader who can jump straight to the techniques they care about. It makes incidents comparable — you can immediately see that this month's ransomware case used the same initial-access technique as last month's, which points to a control gap. And it feeds threat-intelligence products: mapped incidents roll up into a picture of which adversary behaviors your organization actually faces.\n\n### Coverage gaps and the heatmap\n\nThe most strategic use of ATT&CK is measuring detection coverage. The ATT&CK Navigator lets you take the full matrix and color each technique by whether you have a detection for it, how good that detection is, and whether you have ever actually observed it. The result is a heatmap of your defensive posture. Green techniques are well-covered; red or blank techniques are blind spots. When leadership asks \"are we protected against ransomware operators?\" you do not answer with a feeling — you overlay the known techniques of the relevant threat groups onto your coverage map and show exactly which of their techniques you would catch and which you would miss. That gap analysis is how a mature SOC decides where to spend its next detection-engineering hours: you build detections for the red techniques that the adversaries you actually face are known to use.\n\n### The questions mapping lets you answer\n\nOnce your incidents and detections are mapped, you can answer questions that are otherwise unanswerable. **Which techniques do we detect reliably, and which have we never once seen?** (A technique you have never observed might mean you are safe — or that you are blind to it.) **Which tactics are our weakest?** (Many SOCs are strong on Execution and C2 but weak on Discovery and Collection, giving attackers a quiet window to work in.) **Are our detections concentrated on a few noisy techniques while whole tactics go uncovered?** **When a new threat report drops describing an active campaign, which of its techniques would we catch today?** These are the questions that turn a reactive alert-closing operation into a deliberate, measurable defensive program.\n\n### The habit to build\n\nThe practical discipline is simple: map as you go. Tag every alert, investigation, and detection rule with the ATT&CK technique IDs it relates to. It costs seconds per case and compounds into a coverage map, a comparable incident history, and a shared language across the SOC. The analyst who maps consistently can point at the heatmap and say, with evidence, exactly where the organization is strong and where it is exposed.",
        "codeExample": "// From mapped incidents to a coverage decision (ATT&CK Navigator layer, conceptual)\n//\n// Incident report chain (this ransomware case):\n//   T1566.001 Spearphishing Attachment   [DETECTED - mail gw + EDR]\n//   T1204.002 Malicious File             [DETECTED - EDR]\n//   T1059.001 PowerShell                 [DETECTED - Sysmon EID 1]\n//   T1547.001 Registry Run Key           [DETECTED - Sysmon EID 13]\n//   T1071.001 Web Protocols (C2)         [DETECTED - proxy beaconing rule]\n//   T1486     Data Encrypted for Impact  [DETECTED LATE - only at encryption]\n//\n// Coverage gap surfaced by this case:\n//   T1087 Account Discovery              [BLIND - no detection]\n//   T1021.002 SMB Admin Shares (lateral) [BLIND - no detection]\n//   -> Attacker had a quiet window between C2 and Impact.\n//\n// Leadership question: \"Would we catch <ransomware group X>?\"\n//   Overlay group's known techniques onto our layer -> red cells = where we'd miss.\n//   Next detection-engineering sprint targets the red techniques they actually use."
      }
